      {
        "id": 3076771,
        "name": null,
        "username": "PFMay",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/pfmay/{size}/93143_2.png",
        "created_at": "2021-01-21T11:50:44.000Z",
        "cooked": "<p>Surely the practise of buying in grapes to make wine is widespread, negotiants in Bordeaux have been doing so for centuries.</p>\n<p>One could (and they do) argue that one can buy the best grapes produced in each vintage, rather than have to use ones own grapes even in a poor harvest as Bordeaux Chateaux do.</p>\n<p>Brands and Own Labels can keep the same labelling, advertising and brand loyalty while switching grape suppliers from year to year, either to get the quality required or to get  cheaper price.</p>\n<p>Some winemakers who own no vineyards do name the vineyard from where they purchased the grapes, such as Once &amp; Future and Bedrock to name just two\u2026</p>",
        "post_number": 2,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 6,
        "updated_at": "2022-06-04T01:22:42.634Z",
